# Spark Tutor — Cursor Rules
# K-1 AI Tutoring App | Next.js + Firebase + Claude + Gemini
# Last updated: June 2026

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# PROJECT CONTEXT
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Spark Tutor is a K-1 tutoring app where children pick and name
# a mascot character (the Spark Squad), then learn Math and Reading/ELA
# through Socratic AI conversations. Parents get automatic session
# summaries after each session.
#
# Architecture:
#   - Frontend:      Next.js 14 (App Router) + Tailwind CSS + Shadcn UI
#   - Auth + DB:     Firebase Auth + Firestore
#   - Vector search: Firebase Vector Search (RAG index)
#   - RAG model:     Gemini (Google AI Studio) — embeddings + retrieval
#   - Chat model:    Claude (Anthropic API) — mascot voice + Socratic Q&A
#   - Agentic:       Claude — auto session summary on session end
#   - MCP tool:      Custom Next.js API route — math problem generator
#   - State:         Zustand (lightweight global state)
#   - Deployment:    Vercel
#
# Users:
#   - Children (K-1, ages 5-6) use the chat UI with their mascot
#   - Parents create accounts, view dashboards, receive session summaries
#   - No child accounts — all data stored under parent UID (COPPA)


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CODING STYLE & QUALITY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Language
- Use TypeScript for every file — no plain .js files except config
- Enable strict mode in tsconfig.json — never disable it
- Always define types and interfaces; never use `any`
- Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions and primitives
- Export types from a central /types directory when shared across files

# Readability
- Write code as if a junior developer will read it tomorrow
- Prefer explicit, descriptive names over short clever ones
  - BAD:  const d = new Date()
  - GOOD: const sessionStartDate = new Date()
- One concept per function — if a function does two things, split it
- Add a one-line JSDoc comment above every function explaining what it does
- Use blank lines to separate logical sections within a function

# File size
- Hard limit: 500 lines per file — split into smaller modules if approaching this
- Hard limit: 200 lines per component — extract sub-components early
- Each file should have one clear responsibility (single responsibility principle)

# Comments
- Comment the WHY, not the WHAT
  - BAD:  // increment counter
  - GOOD: // track stars separately from score so we can animate them independently
- Add a file-level comment at the top of every file explaining its purpose
- Mark todos clearly: // TODO: add voice input in v2

# Formatting
- Use Prettier defaults (enforced via .prettierrc)
- 2-space indentation
- Single quotes for strings
- Trailing commas in multi-line objects and arrays
- Max line length: 100 characters


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# NEXT.JS CONVENTIONS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# App Router structure
- Use the App Router exclusively — no Pages Router
- Every route segment gets its own folder under /app
- Keep page.tsx files thin — logic lives in components, not pages
- Use layout.tsx for shared UI (nav, auth wrappers)
- Use loading.tsx and error.tsx for every major route segment

# Server vs Client components
- Default to Server Components — only add 'use client' when needed
- 'use client' is needed for: useState, useEffect, event handlers, Zustand, Firebase listeners
- Never fetch data in a Client Component if a Server Component can do it
- Keep 'use client' components as small as possible — push them to leaf nodes

# API routes
- All AI calls (Claude, Gemini) go through /app/api routes — never call AI APIs from the client
- Never expose API keys to the browser — always server-side only
- Name API routes clearly: /api/chat, /api/summary, /api/mcp/math-problem
- Every API route must handle errors and return consistent response shapes:
  { success: boolean, data?: unknown, error?: string }

# Data fetching
- Use Firebase onSnapshot for real-time data (session updates, parent dashboard)
- Use Firebase getDoc/getDocs for one-time reads
- Always handle loading and error states — never assume data is available
- Cancel Firestore listeners in useEffect cleanup functions


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# COMPONENT ARCHITECTURE
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# File structure
src/
  app/                      # Next.js App Router pages and API routes
    (auth)/                 # Auth group: login, signup
    (child)/                # Child-facing routes: character select, chat
    (parent)/               # Parent-facing routes: dashboard, session history
    api/                    # Server-side API routes
      chat/                 # Claude conversation endpoint
      summary/              # Agentic session summary endpoint
      mcp/                  # MCP tool endpoints
        math-problem/       # Math problem generator
      rag/                  # RAG retrieval endpoint
  components/               # Reusable UI components
    ui/                     # Shadcn UI components (auto-generated, do not edit)
    child/                  # Child-specific components (CharacterCard, ChatBubble, StarBurst)
    parent/                 # Parent-specific components (SessionSummaryCard, ProgressPanel)
    shared/                 # Shared across child and parent (LoadingSpinner, ErrorMessage)
  lib/                      # Utility functions and service clients
    firebase/               # Firebase init and helper functions
    claude/                 # Claude API client and prompt builders
    gemini/                 # Gemini embedding and retrieval functions
    mcp/                    # MCP tool definitions
  store/                    # Zustand state stores
  types/                    # Shared TypeScript types and interfaces
  constants/                # App-wide constants (character definitions, subjects)
  hooks/                    # Custom React hooks (useSession, useAuth, useStars)

# Naming conventions
- Components:    PascalCase  (CharacterSelectionScreen.tsx)
- Hooks:         camelCase with 'use' prefix (useSessionSummary.ts)
- Utilities:     camelCase (buildSystemPrompt.ts)
- Constants:     SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (MAX_SESSION_STARS)
- Types:         PascalCase with descriptive suffix (SessionSummaryType, CharacterConfig)
- API routes:    kebab-case folders (math-problem, session-end)

# Component rules
- Every component gets its own file — no multi-component files
- Props must be typed with an interface named [ComponentName]Props
- Destructure props at the top of every component
- Keep JSX readable — extract complex conditional rendering into variables
- Example:

  interface CharacterCardProps {
    character: CharacterConfig;
    isSelected: boolean;
    onSelect: (id: string) => void;
  }

  export function CharacterCard({ character, isSelected, onSelect }: CharacterCardProps) {
    const cardClasses = isSelected ? 'ring-4 ring-yellow-400' : '';

    return (
      <button
        className={`rounded-2xl p-4 ${cardClasses}`}
        onClick={() => onSelect(character.id)}
      >
        {/* character content */}
      </button>
    );
  }


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# FIREBASE RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Auth
- Only parents create accounts — children never authenticate directly
- Always check auth state before accessing Firestore — never assume logged in
- Use Firebase Auth onAuthStateChanged in a top-level AuthProvider component
- Redirect unauthenticated users to /login from protected routes

# Firestore
- Never write directly to Firestore from a component — always go through a service function in /lib/firebase
- Always use the typed converter pattern for Firestore documents
- Structure all child session data under the parent UID:
  users/{parentUID}/sessions/{sessionID}
- Never store child real names, ages, photos, or any PII
- The only "child" data stored is: character type, character name chosen by child (not real name)
- Always include error handling on every read and write operation

# Security rules (firestore.rules)
- Users can only read/write their own documents
- No public read/write access on any collection
- Validate data shape in rules — reject malformed writes

# Environment variables
- Firebase config goes in .env.local — never hardcode credentials
- All env vars accessed server-side only through /lib/firebase/config.ts
- Prefix client-safe vars with NEXT_PUBLIC_ (only Firebase client config needs this)
- Never log env vars or API keys — not even in development


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# AI & PROMPT ENGINEERING RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Claude (conversation)
- All Claude calls go through /app/api/chat — never call from the client
- Always compose the system prompt from three separate layers:
    1. BASE_TUTOR_RULES   — never changes, enforces K-1 safety and Socratic method
    2. CHARACTER_VOICE    — loaded from /constants/characters.ts based on selected character
    3. RAG_CONTEXT        — curriculum chunks retrieved from Firebase Vector Search
- Stream Claude responses using the Anthropic streaming API for better UX
- Always set max_tokens to a reasonable limit (300 for child chat, 600 for parent summary)
- Always set temperature to 0.7 for child chat (warm but consistent)
- Log token usage in development to monitor costs

# Gemini (RAG)
- Gemini is used ONLY for creating embeddings and retrieving curriculum chunks
- Gemini is NOT used for generating conversation — that is Claude's job
- Retrieve top 3 most relevant chunks per child message
- Filter retrieved chunks by subject and grade_band metadata before returning
- Cache embeddings — never re-embed a document that is already in Firebase Vector Search

# Prompt safety rules
- BASE_TUTOR_RULES must include explicit instruction to stay on Math and Reading/ELA only
- Claude must be instructed to never discuss personal topics, current events, or anything outside curriculum
- If a child input seems off-topic, the mascot redirects warmly back to the lesson
- Never include child input verbatim in a log or database field — summarize only

# MCP tool
- The math problem generator MCP tool lives at /app/api/mcp/math-problem
- It accepts: { grade: 'K' | '1', topic: string, difficulty: 'easy' | 'medium' }
- It returns: { problem: string, hint: string, answer: string }
- The answer field is NEVER sent to the client — server-side only
- Claude uses the problem and hint only; it guides the child Socratically toward the answer


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ZUSTAND STATE MANAGEMENT
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# What goes in Zustand (global state)
- Active character selection (id, chosen name)
- Current session data (sessionId, subject, messageCount, starsEarned)
- Auth state mirror (parentUID, isAuthenticated) — mirrors Firebase Auth
- UI state that crosses multiple components (isChatLoading, isSessionEnding)

# What stays in local state (useState)
- Input field values
- Component-level toggle states (dropdown open/closed)
- Animation triggers

# Store structure
- One store per domain: useChildStore, useSessionStore, useAuthStore
- Keep stores small — max 8-10 fields per store
- Always define the full TypeScript interface for each store
- Use shallow equality checks when selecting multiple fields from a store

# Example store pattern:
  interface SessionStore {
    sessionId: string | null;
    subject: 'math' | 'reading' | null;
    starsEarned: number;
    messageCount: number;
    startSession: (subject: 'math' | 'reading') => void;
    addStar: () => void;
    endSession: () => void;
  }


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# UI / TAILWIND RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Child UI (ages 5-6 — these are non-negotiable)
- Minimum touch target size: 48x48px on all interactive elements
- Minimum font size: 18px for any text the child reads
- Use rounded-2xl or rounded-3xl for all child-facing cards and buttons
- Bright, saturated colors — this is a kids app, not a SaaS dashboard
- Every interactive element must have a visible hover AND focus state
- Never rely on color alone to convey meaning — add an icon or label too
- Keep the child chat UI to a single column — no side panels on mobile

# Parent UI
- Clean and minimal — parents want information, not excitement
- Use Shadcn UI components for the parent dashboard (Card, Table, Badge)
- Standard readable font sizes (16px minimum)
- Neutral color palette with one accent color for important actions

# Tailwind conventions
- Use Tailwind utility classes directly — no custom CSS unless absolutely necessary
- Group Tailwind classes in this order: layout → spacing → sizing → color → typography → effects
- Extract long class strings into a variable when they exceed one line:
  const buttonClasses = 'flex items-center justify-center min-h-[48px] rounded-2xl bg-yellow-400 text-lg font-bold hover:bg-yellow-300 active:scale-95 transition-all'
- Use the cn() utility (from shadcn) for conditional class merging — not template literals

# Shadcn UI
- Use Shadcn components for the parent dashboard and auth screens
- Do NOT use Shadcn components in the child chat UI — build custom kid-friendly components there
- Never modify files inside /components/ui — extend them with wrapper components instead
- Install components with: npx shadcn@latest add [component-name]


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ERROR HANDLING
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# General rules
- Every async function must be wrapped in try/catch
- Never swallow errors silently — always log or surface them
- Distinguish between user-facing errors (show in UI) and dev errors (log only)
- API routes must always return a response — never leave a request hanging

# Child-facing errors
- Never show technical error messages to a child
- On AI call failure: mascot says something warm like "Hmm, let me think for a second... try asking me again!"
- On network error: show a friendly "Something went wrong — let's try again" with a retry button

# Parent-facing errors
- Clear, plain English — "We couldn't load your session history. Please refresh."
- Always offer a retry action
- Log errors to console in development with full context

# TypeScript error handling pattern
  type ApiResult<T> = 
    | { success: true; data: T }
    | { success: false; error: string };

  // Use this return type on all API route handlers and service functions


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECURITY & PRIVACY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# COPPA compliance (children under 13)
- Never collect child's real name, age, school, photo, or location
- The only identity stored for a child is: character type + character name (fictional)
- All session data is owned by the parent account (parent UID)
- Never build features that allow children to communicate with other users

# API security
- Rate limit all AI API routes — use Vercel's built-in rate limiting or upstash/ratelimit
- Validate and sanitize all user input before sending to Claude or Gemini
- Never include raw user input in database keys or query parameters
- Always verify Firebase Auth token on every protected API route:
  const token = await admin.auth().verifyIdToken(authHeader)

# Environment & secrets
- .env.local is gitignored — never commit it
- Add all required env var names (without values) to .env.example
- Rotate API keys immediately if accidentally exposed


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# TESTING & QUALITY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# For this MVP, focus on:
- TypeScript types catching bugs at compile time (your primary safety net)
- Manual testing of all AI flows before each weekly milestone
- Test on mobile viewport (375px wide) — the child UI must work on a tablet

# Things to manually test every week
- Character selection and naming flow end-to-end
- Chat session: send 5 messages, verify Socratic responses, verify stars increment
- RAG retrieval: ask a curriculum question, verify answer references real content
- Session end: verify parent summary appears on dashboard within 5 seconds
- Parent auth: login, logout, protected route redirect

# Code quality before committing
- No TypeScript errors (run: npx tsc --noEmit)
- No unused imports or variables
- No console.log statements in production code (use a logger utility)
- Run Prettier before every commit (add as a pre-commit hook with husky)


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# GIT CONVENTIONS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Commit message format
# type(scope): short description
#
# Types: feat | fix | refactor | style | docs | chore
# Scope: child-ui | parent-ui | api | rag | mcp | auth | store | types
#
# Examples:
#   feat(child-ui): add character selection screen with 6 spark squad cards
#   feat(api): add claude chat endpoint with composable system prompt
#   feat(rag): add gemini embedding ingestion script for k-1 math content
#   fix(auth): redirect unauthenticated users to login from parent dashboard
#   refactor(store): split session store into child and session domains
#   chore: add prettier and husky pre-commit hook

# Branch strategy (simple, solo developer)
- main:    production — only merge when a weekly milestone is complete
- dev:     active development — commit here daily
- feature/ branches for anything that takes more than one session to build


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# THINGS TO NEVER DO
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Never call Claude or Gemini APIs directly from a React component
- Never store API keys in client-side code or .env files without NEXT_PUBLIC_ awareness
- Never store child PII (name, age, photo, location) — ever
- Never use `any` in TypeScript
- Never use inline styles in JSX — use Tailwind classes
- Never create a component over 200 lines without splitting it
- Never create a file over 500 lines without refactoring
- Never send the MCP math problem answer to the client
- Never disable TypeScript strict mode
- Never commit with console.logs or TODO-hacks left in production code paths
- Never use the Pages Router — App Router only